Before Messi and Ronaldo, players did not usually have long peaks. Between say 2004-07, Ronaldinho and Henry were considered the best

>Where do they rank all time?
At the time, the hype around Ronaldinho was unprecedented. For the first time since Maradona people were calling someone the GOAT. The Nike ad, video games (FIFA/ FIFAstreet), the el Classico standing ovation all added to the mystique

It's all advertising (as people will find out about Messi and Ronaldo later). Ronaldinho was the first to utilise mass marketing just as YouTube took off, and the online aspect of it all was just coming into play, and new mass markets (India for instance) were just emerging

The NFL is so much more successful than other leagues in part because they're much more perceptive and adaptive. Which is why I hope the currently shitty officiating will be addressed soon. Its a programming thing, money is stored in the program as a signed 32 bit integer which means the highest value possible is (2^31) - 1 or a little over 2.147 billion if they made the simple change of storing money as a 64 bit signed integer the highest possible value would be (2^63) -1.
Although the reason they possibly don't change this is because the number a 64 bit integer can hold is so large no one would feasibly get that much money and 64 bit integers will take up more space in the program doubling the amount of space required to store the amount of money each team has. Although with modern systems it wouldn't matter SI target shitty laptops with their game.

>>129012185
i did a save with england, germany, spain, italy, portugal, brazil, argentina loaded, and left the detail level at the default setting. after 15 years, the teams from the top 5 leagues dominated forever. the champions league, europa league, and conference league is always won by a team from one of those leagues. there is very little variance even at the group stage level of competitions. maybe you see like psv instead of anderlecht make it to the r16 one season. but by the time it gets to the quarter finals its only going to be teams from the big5 leagues, maybe benfica or porto sneak in.

i tried a different save with 15+ euro countrys loaded, and changed the detail level to "all competitive matches" just for the top leagues. there is still little variance, and the teams from the top 5 leagues do still dominate the continental competition, but i did begin to see a bit of variance at the group stage and 1st knockout rounds, especially in the europa and conference leagues. mainly with teams from the leagues i had loaded.

the main thing is that by loading the other leagues, it actually gives those teams a schedule and players. when it is an unloaded league, you end up playing against a team of grey players who have no scheduled games other than the continental competition. the grey "fake" players the game gives these teams, especially in smaller countrys with lower reputation, are absolutely terrible. i wouldnt be surprised if a loaded championship, segunda division, ligue2, serieb team would destroy an unloaded greyed out anderlecht or basel or shakhtar or other good team from a smaller country.

2pt FG%
Kareem .560
LeBron .554
Jordan .510

3pt FG%
LeBron .344
Jordan .327
Kareem .056

FT%
Jordan .835
LeBron .735
Kareem .721

Rebounds per game
Kareem 11.2
LeBron 7.5
Jordan 6.2

Assists per game
LeBron 7.3
Jordan 5.3
Kareem 3.6

Points per game
Jordan 30.1
LeBron 27.2
Kareem 24.6

This sums up their games pretty well and tells you their roles and what kind of players they were.

Jordan scored more points per game despite a lower shooting percentage. That means he got the ball all the time. If he shot as accurately as LeBron, he would be the biggest scorer ever. He was not a lot better than Kobe.

Kareem never shot 3s. He posted up in the key and got fed the ball and scored at will. If he missed, he got the rebound and tried again or fed it to Magic.

Lebron did everything. He passed, he got rebounds, he was a better shooter than MJ, but didn't take as many shots because he was always passing to the open player.

This isn't even a discussion. There is nothing that MJ was better than LeBron at other than taking a lot more shots every game.
